would sustain it momentarily. Then they
would tip or sink. There would be foothold
only through the instant required to choose
another foothold and leap towards it.

Always, moreover, the leap would have to be
taken from sinking ground. When they came,
by good chance, to a pan that would bear them
up for a moment, they would have instantly to
discover another heavy block to which to shape
their agitated course. There would be no rest       no
certainty beyond the impending moment.
But leaping thus       alert and agile and daring       a
man might              

Might? Mm-m       a man might! And he
might not! There were contingencies. A man
might leap short and find black water where he
had depended upon a footing of ice       a man
might land on the edge of a pan and fall slowly
back for sheer lack of power to obtain a balance       a
